"correctResponses":null,"explanation":"\u003Cp\u003EThe image shows \u003Cstrong\u003Eneutrophil infiltration\u003C/strong\u003E in the pancreatic tissue. While \u003Cstrong\u003Esaponification\u003C/strong\u003E is a characteristic finding in acute pancreatitis, it is only visible macroscopically as chalky white areas where pancreatic enzymes have digested fat. \u003Cstrong\u003EFat necrosis\u003C/strong\u003E appears as ghost-like outlines of adipocytes with basophilic calcium deposits. \u003Cstrong\u003EParenchymal necrosis\u003C/strong\u003E would show complete destruction of acinar architecture. \u003Cstrong\u003EHaemorrhage\u003C/strong\u003E would appear as extensive red blood cell extravasation.\u003C/p\u003E","optionExplanations":["","","","",""],"learningPoints":["Acute pancreatitis shows characteristic histological features including neutrophilic infiltration, fat necrosis, parenchymal necrosis and haemorrhage","Saponification is the chemical process where pancreatic lipase breaks down fat cells, creating chalky white areas visible macroscopically"],"references":["\u0022Tryptic fat tissue necrosis in severe pancreatitis.\u0022 by Patho is licensed under Creative Commons Attribution-Share Alike 3.0 Unported license. https://commons.wikimedia.org/wiki/Category:Histopathology_of_acute_pancreatitis#/media/File:Tryptic_fat_tissue_necrosis_in_severe_pancreatitis,_HE_1.JPG","Nightingale, J. M. (2012). Applied anatomy and physiology of the gastrointestinal tract (GIT). Gastrointestinal Tract Imaging E-Book: Gastrointestinal Tract Imaging E-Book, 45","Podolsky, D. K., Camilleri, M., Fitz, J. G., Kalloo, A. N., Shanahan, F., \u0026 Wang, T. C. (Eds.). (2015). Yamada\u0027s textbook of gastroenterology. John Wiley \u0026 Sons","Yamada, T., Alpers, D. H., Kalloo, A. N., Kaplowitz, N., Owyang, C., \u0026 Powell, D. W. (Eds.). (2011). Textbook of gastroenterology. John Wiley \u0026 Sons"]},"relationships":{"itemRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"55297"}},"